From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] drivers/ps4: Option B v3 - bpcie domain as 6.x MSI parent

Linux 6.2 reworked PCI MSI domain lookup so that dev_set_msi_domain()
only takes effect when the installed domain is itself marked as an
MSI parent (IRQ_DOMAIN_FLAG_MSI_PARENT) and provides msi_parent_ops::
init_dev_msi_info.  The kernel's PCI MSI core now follows this path:

  pci_msi_setup_msi_irqs()                       drivers/pci/msi/irqdomain.c
   └─ dev_get_msi_domain(&dev->dev)              # lookup
      └─ irq_domain_is_hierarchy(domain)
         └─ msi_domain_alloc_irqs_all_locked(...)
            └─ ... eventually
               msi_create_device_irq_domain() {
                 if (!irq_domain_is_msi_parent(parent))   <-- BAILS if not parent
                     return false;
                 if (!pops->init_dev_msi_info(...))       <-- BAILS without parent ops
                     goto fail;
               }

Three things were broken on Baikal under 6.x:

  (1) bpcie's per-function MSI domain was not marked as an MSI parent
      → kernel rejected it.
  (2) bpcie did not provide msi_parent_ops → kernel had no way to
      construct per-device child domains for xhci/sdhci/ahci/sky2 etc.
  (3) bpcie never called dev_set_msi_domain() on any Baikal pdev — so
      even after (1)+(2), child PCI devices wouldn't find the parent
      via dev_get_msi_domain() and would fall back to the default x86
      vector domain.  This was a latent bug from the 5.4 → 6.x port:
      under 5.4 the legacy fwnode-based PCI MSI lookup walked the
      irq_domain_list and matched our "Baikal-MSI" name; in 6.2+ that
      lookup was replaced by dev->msi.domain field-only, so the
      install became no longer optional.

History:
  v1 - parent flag + parent_ops only.  Boot test: marked domain as
       MSI parent 8x, but bpcie_init_dev_msi_info never fired.  Kernel
       still routed via default x86 vector → 0xef spurious.
  v2 - v1 + dev_set_msi_domain() install in bpcie_create_irq_domains().
       Boot test: hung at exactly 4.63s, right after the 8th
       "marked ... as MSI parent" log line, with serial silence after.
       Cause: our custom init_dev_msi_info wrapper recursed because it
       called real_parent->msi_parent_ops->init_dev_msi_info — but
       real_parent IS the MSI parent the kernel found (us), so
       msi_parent_ops is OUR ops, and we called ourselves until stack
       overflow took down the kernel.  USB keyboard worked from the v2
       boot, suggesting xHCI MSIs were being delivered (likely via the
       legacy fallback path before bpcie's own pdev hit the recursion).
  v3 - replace the recursing wrapper with the kernel-provided helper
       msi_parent_init_dev_msi_info().  The helper walks domain->parent
       explicitly (the next level UP in the irq_domain hierarchy, i.e.
       x86_vector_domain) and dispatches to its msi_parent_ops, which
       avoids the self-reference loop.

Caveat — minimum-viable shape:

  This patch installs the standard PCI MSI handler (handle_edge_irq via
  x86 vector inheritance) on the per-device child domain rather than
  bpcie_handle_edge_irq.  Reason: the bpcie subfunction demuxer relies
  on irq_find_mapping(desc->irq_data.domain, initial_hwirq + i) to
  walk sibling subfunctions in the SAME domain.  In the new per-device
  model each pdev has its own domain, so that lookup pattern no longer
  resolves siblings.

  This is fine for xHCI single-vector MSI (no demuxing needed — the
  one MSI vector lands on xhci_irq directly).  If SDHCI/AHCI/sky2/etc.
  end up needing the demuxer for IRQ delivery on Baikal, the demuxer
  itself will need porting to the per-device model (override info->handler
  in init_dev_msi_info AND rework the sibling lookup to walk dev->parent's
  msi.data->__domains[]).  Track as follow-up.

Diagnostic: pr_info() in bpcie_create_irq_domain so we can confirm in UART
that the MSI parent flag is set on each Baikal function's domain.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <17146298+meerzulee@users.noreply.github.com>
---
--- a/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie.c
+++ b/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie.c
@@ -371,6 +371,27 @@
 	#endif
 }
 
+/*
+ * Option B v3 (Linux 6.2+ per-device MSI rework):
+ *
+ * Use the kernel-provided helper msi_parent_init_dev_msi_info() which
+ * walks domain->parent (the next-level-up in the irq_domain hierarchy,
+ * i.e. x86_vector_domain) and dispatches to its msi_parent_ops.
+ *
+ * v2 had a custom wrapper that recursed because it dereferenced
+ * real_parent->msi_parent_ops — but real_parent IS the MSI parent the
+ * kernel found (us), not the next-level-up. That self-reference caused
+ * infinite recursion → stack overflow → kernel hung at exactly the moment
+ * bpcie's own pdev called pci_alloc_irq_vectors(). The kernel helper
+ * walks domain->parent explicitly so it doesn't recurse.
+ */
+static const struct msi_parent_ops bpcie_msi_parent_ops = {
+	.supported_flags	= MSI_GENERIC_FLAGS_MASK | MSI_FLAG_PCI_MSIX |
+				  MSI_FLAG_MULTI_PCI_MSI,
+	.init_dev_msi_info	= msi_parent_init_dev_msi_info,
+	.prefix			= "bpcie-",
+};
+
 struct irq_domain *bpcie_create_irq_domain(struct bpcie_dev *sc, struct pci_dev *pdev)//similar to hpet_create_irq_domain
 {
 	struct irq_domain *domain, *parent;
@@ -413,8 +434,32 @@
 	if (!domain) {
 		irq_domain_free_fwnode(fn);
 		pr_warn("Failed to initialize Baikal-MSI irqdomain.\n");
+		return NULL;
 	}
 
+	/*
+	 * Option B: mark this domain as a 6.x MSI parent so that the kernel's
+	 * pci_msi_setup_msi_irqs path will walk it instead of falling through
+	 * to the default x86 vector domain (which would deliver MSIs as
+	 * APIC_SPURIOUS_VECTOR (0xef) on the LAPIC and lose them).
+	 */
+	domain->flags |= IRQ_DOMAIN_FLAG_MSI_PARENT;
+	domain->msi_parent_ops = &bpcie_msi_parent_ops;
+	/*
+	 * Option B v4: x86's x86_init_dev_msi_info() (the kernel helper we
+	 * delegate to via msi_parent_init_dev_msi_info) gates on
+	 * real_parent->bus_token: only DOMAIN_BUS_ANY (which requires
+	 * domain == real_parent — for x86_vector itself), DOMAIN_BUS_DMAR,
+	 * and DOMAIN_BUS_AMDVI are accepted; everything else WARN()s and
+	 * returns false (causing all child MSI allocs to fail with
+	 * -EPROBE_DEFER).  Pretend to be AMDVI — semantically the closest
+	 * (AMD platform, intermediate MSI-routing parent) and architecturally
+	 * the role bpcie plays between x86_vector and Baikal child PCI devs.
+	 */
+	irq_domain_update_bus_token(domain, DOMAIN_BUS_AMDVI);
+	pr_info("bpcie_create_irq_domain: marked %s as MSI parent (flags=0x%x bus_token=AMDVI)\n",
+		domain->name, domain->flags);
+
 	return domain;
 }
 
@@ -495,6 +540,16 @@
 		if (bpcie_pdev) {
 			struct irq_domain * domain = bpcie_create_irq_domain(sc, bpcie_pdev);
 			if (func == BAIKAL_FUNC_ID_PCIE) sc->irqdomain = domain;
+			/*
+			 * Option B (continued): install the domain on this pdev so that
+			 * the 6.x PCI MSI core (pci_msi_setup_msi_irqs →
+			 * dev_get_msi_domain) actually finds it. Without this the
+			 * domain is marked MSI parent but unreachable; the kernel
+			 * falls back to the default x86 vector domain and MSIs are
+			 * delivered as APIC_SPURIOUS_VECTOR (0xef).
+			 */
+			if (domain)
+				dev_set_msi_domain(&bpcie_pdev->dev, domain);
 			pci_dev_put(bpcie_pdev);
 		} else
 			sc_err("cannot find bpcie func %d device", func);
